The "miracle" recovery of a Peshawar massacre survivor
A paralysed teenager who had been shot four times in Pakistan’s most brutal terrorist attack managed a “miracle” recovery after treatment in the United Kingdom.
Mohamed Ibrahim Khan, 13 years old, the Pakistani doctors had told him that he would never be able to go.
At least 140 people, most children, were killed when armed men attacked the public school of the Peshawar army last December.
Mohamed, who arrived in London last month for surgery, will be released later from the hospital.
Just nine months ago, on a regular Tuesday morning, Mohamed was sitting at first aid time and listening carefully to his teachers.
Even then, seven armed men dressed in security uniforms entered the army's public school.
They carried belts with explosives and had to carry out a simple mission: to kill all the men, women and children in their way.
“I can’t forget what happened that day,” Mohamed says with a rough look.
I was sitting in the amphitheater, asking questions... then I heard gunshots outside.
The terrorists went inside and started killing.
Mohamed describes how he took four students out of the amphitheater while the carnagi was taking place.
Then he says he heard his friend, Hamza, screaming him.
He said, "Oh, brother, save me."
I held him by the hand.
Then I was shot in the back, and he in the head.
Most of the people killed in the attack were students
Hamza died in Mohamed's arms.
Mohamed remembers that immediately after that he fainted and that the next thing he knew was that he was on a hospital bed, paralyzed from the waist down.
The doctors in Peshawar in northern Pakistan, then the doctors in Rawalpindi, near the capital, told his family that there was no treatment and he would never be able to go.
“When I saw him, I felt my soul coming out,” says Sher Khan, Mohamed’s father.
Those nine months were the hardest in my life.
But Khan and his wife, Sherbano, refused to believe that their son so passionate about cricket would never be able to use his feet again.
They did a campaign and asked for help from Pakistani television, attracting support from famous people like Imran Khan, who became a politician.
In the end, they managed to raise funds to take Mohamed to the United Kingdom and give him treatment at the Harley Street private clinic in London.
The consultant's neurosurgeon Irfan Malik described Mohamed as "fearful" when he reached the hospital.
“He had spent the last [some] months lying in bed, without being able to move from one side to another, says Malik.
He was weak, he put a lot of pressure on his back.
He wasn't in too good shape.
A vertebrae from the base of Mohamed's vertebrae column had been destroyed
Mohamed had been shot in his shoulder, hip and back during the attack, and the lower spine had been destroyed, leading to paralysis.
However, during a six-hour operation, Malik and his team managed to rewire the nerve endings and rebuild the destroyed part of the column.
Even Malik was surprised at what happened next.
Just a week after the operation, Mohamed got up and started taking steps and going.
We didn't expect such a good outcome.
It was a miracle," he says.
In less than two weeks after the operation, Mohamed is ready to leave the hospital and start the long recovery process.
Mohamed challenged fate and began to go again
He wants to become strong and continue his studies in the United Kingdom.
But he is determined to return to Pakistan, join the army and fight terrorism.
"It's like I still have a chance to live," he says, showing the pictures with weapons drawn by him next to school textbooks and pens
Physically, Mohamed becomes increasingly powerful every day, but psychological trauma through which he goes and now is unimaginable.
"My anger has not fallen," he confesses.
In my school, little kids were killed.
What crime did they commit?
His mother wipes a tear, comforts the growing one, and says: “I see my son walking again.”
He'll be able to continue to be alive.
