He told BBC about his love for vinyl and his loaded program and explained how comedy actor Matt Berry got to open his shows.
What does vinyl mean to you?
I grew up even in the end of the vinyl era, and I remember that at that time I was just waiting for the CD to appear, because the vinyl was so annoying.
You were buying a record, going with him home, having a scratch and you had to bring him back.
I love CDs, and for certain types of music, for example the classic one, they're better than vinyls.
But the problem with CDs and digital downloads is that there is nothing else you really value.
Having a vinyl is like having a nice painting hanging in the living room.
It's something you can hold in hand, while you get absorbed by the lyrics and overwhelmed by the artistic act.
I thought it was just a nostalgic thing, but there's no way that if a kid too young to remember the vinyls they like this kind of experience.
Do you have any vinyl you especially hold in?
I admit I got rid of all the vinyl in the '90s.
All the wines I've got are bought again.
I started with the idea of restoring the collection I was 15 years old, but I'm past that limit.
The first record I got my parents to buy was Out of the Blue from Electric Light Orchestra.
If I still had the original copy, it would have had sentimental value, but unfortunately it is somewhere through a charity store.
Steven Wilson hopes the album will be a gateway to possible new fans
Why did you launch your new Transience compilation on vinyl?
It was originally designed as an idea for the record day, but I missed the opportunity.
My home suggested to gather a few of my shorter and more accessible songs.
I became easily obsessed with the idea of doing something like "introducing into Steven Wilson's music" and I had necessarily kept the project to be launched only on vinyl.
Who buys vinyl also receives a download version at high resolution.
Are you worried that the album won't show your music in its real light?
No, because, although I focus on longer music, there's one thing I've always valued above anything: the melodic part.
There is a lot of progressive rock that focuses more on technical complexity than on the melodic side.
Pink Floyd, the most famous progressive rock band of all time, has passed the time test because they have always put the emphasis on the melodic side and the atmosphere.
What are you preparing for Albert Hall shows?
I don't want you to reveal too much.
The repertoire will be completely different every night.
In the first, it will be a version of Hand's show. Erase. which we had this year, but on steroids, with a few guests.
The second night will be rather an incursion into my history, it being more oriented towards the fans who followed me over the years.
How did you choose Matt Berry to open your show on the second night?
And me and the rest of the tour team are big fans of [the comedy series on Channel 4] Toast of London, to the point where we always get quoted from it.
I thought I'd listen to Matt's music, too, so I bought him his album, Music for Insomniacs.
I talked to him about our common love for Mike Oldfield and I asked him to sing at the Royal Albert Hall.
Looks like I'm extremely lucky to have him in the opening.
You remixed albums of some bands like XTC, Tears for Fears and Yes.
How much does that affect your own music?
I'm not consciously inspired by this, but, inevitably, when you deconstruct these classic albums, they remain in your mind.
My last solo album, The Raven That Refused to Sing, was without a doubt the most progressive old school album I ever created.
I don't think it was a coincidence that I remixed King Crimson, Jethro Tull and Yes almost all the year before.
The current album, Hand Erase, is much more open, because we were working at Tears for Fears and XTC.
You're often described as the busiest progressive rock musician.
Is that how you feel?
You can delete the word progressive.
I think I'm probably one of the most obsessed people in today's music world and I'm not saying that with pride, because, please believe me, it's a curse.
I think I inherited that from my father, who has an ethic of incredibly powerful work.
If I don't do anything for a whole day, I'm starting to feel guilty.
That's why remix work was a gift, because it means I don't have to do all the time just my music.
The music industry is a tough place to do your career.
Now I wouldn't recommend this to anyone as a profession.
I work every day and I'm not rich, but I live well.
I love what I do, it's a privilege, but if I were lazy I don't think I would have survived.
