A new study shows that more people die from air pollution than malaria and HIV/AIDS
According to a new reference study, over 3 million people die early each year because of air pollution from outside, more than malaria and HIV/AIDS together.
The main cause, especially in Asia, is wood and charcoal burned for housing and cooking, but research reveals that a similar alarming reason is the agricultural emissions from Europe and the United States, where it is the main reason for these deaths.
The report warns that if no action is taken, the number of deaths - already equivalent to six deaths per minute - will double by 2050.
"These projections should trigger an alarm signal for public health agencies all over the world," said Professor Michael Jerrett, environmental health expert at the University of California, who was not involved in research.
Most of the deaths caused by the rain of the air are caused by tiny particles that can be inhaled deep into the lungs.
They cause stroke and stroke, which are responsible for three quarters of the 3.3 million deaths annually, while the rest are caused by lung cancer and respiratory diseases.
Research has not included the effects of indoor air pollution, e.g. from cooking fires, which are estimated to cause 3.4 million more deaths per year.
The new study, published in Nature newspaper, is the first one to highlight various sources of outdoor air pollution and estimated the number of premature deaths caused by them, taking into account road traffic, fossil fuel-based plants and other sources.
Researchers have used a detailed computerized model of the global atmosphere to assess the impact of air pollution on different populations, including new information on how pollution affects Chinese and Indian residents.
A third of all premature deaths were the result of the use of smoke-extinguishing fuels, such as wood and coal, for heating homes or cooking, and the use of dirty diesel generators for electricity, all of which are recognised dangers.
The consumption of this type of internal energy causes half of the 645 000 annual deaths in India and a third of the 1.4 million annual deaths in China.
However, the research found that agricultural ammonia emissions had a "remarkable" impact, according to Professor Jos Lelieveld of the German Chemical Max Planck Institute, which led the research.
A fifth of global deaths are caused by these emissions, mainly from cattle, birds and pigs and from the over-use of fertilizers.
Amoniaul reacts with traffic and industry exhaust gases and produces tiny particles, being the main reason of the deaths due to air pollution in the east of the United States, Japan and Europe.
"For London, agriculture is the main source," says Lelieveld.
Throughout the United Kingdom, 48% of premature deaths were the result of agricultural pollution.
Traffic pollution is still an important factor in developed countries, causing a fifth of the deaths, despite measures against polluting vehicles.
This has caused only 5% of deaths globally, but the figure could increase as more and more cars appear on the streets in developing countries.
Air pollution by the power plant, in particular by those operating with coal, was significant globally, causing one of seven deaths.
In the US it is the main single factor, causing a third of the 55,000 deaths annually, compared to 16% in the United Kingdom.
Natural air pollution, especially in the arid regions and with much dust, caused almost a fifth of the global deaths caused by air pollution.
This source is a major factor in some arid countries, being responsible for 92% of the deaths in Egypt and 81% in Iran.
"Sustainment between the high degree of pollution and the high number of residents says the word about public health, but there is no longer any knowledge of pollution sources responsible for premature deaths," says Jerrett.
The results are surprising and potentially important for the protection of public health at global level.
It is currently assumed that all particles are as toxic.
However, if fuel burning is more toxic, as some scientists suspect, the percentage of premature deaths that can be attributed to agricultural emissions would be lower.
Even so, Jerrett says "discovery is very valuable... because agriculture has not generally been seen as a major source of air pollution or premature death and suggests that much more attention should be paid to agricultural sources, both from scientists and political leaders."
Dr. Oliver Wild, an atmosphere specialist at Lancaster University in the United Kingdom, said: “The study really stresses the need for air quality control in order to avoid these deaths, especially in areas very populated in Asia.”
