A group of researchers from the Australian Adelaide University conducted a data review for 49 000 women from the Danish National Birth cohort to discover the effects of SSRI administration on the behaviour of children up to the age of 7.
The study found that untreated depression in pregnant women was associated with an increased risk of behavioural problems.
In 210 children whose mothers had been treated with SSRI depression, there was no increased risk of behavioural problems compared with 231 children who were more prone to behavioural problems such as hyperactivity, lack of attention and socialization problems.
The same group of Australian researchers also found in a separate study that mothers are more likely to bleed after birth if they are treated with SSRI.
Analysis of medical data from 30,198 who were born at a university hospital in Adelaide between 2002 and 2008 showed that the risk of postnatal bleeding increased by 5% between 11 and 16% if women were treated with SSRI.
The risk of severe bleeding or postnatal anaemia has doubled, researchers reported.
Researchers said that, although the study linked the administration of SSRI with increased risk, there are a large number of variables - from medicines taken during birth to the limited amount of information that researchers had about women's specific medical conditions - that could have had an effect on the potential for bleeding.
“It is possible for women who have taken antidepressants at an advanced pregnancy stage to have been those with the most severe stage of the disease, and this is the reason for the increased risk of postnatal bleeding, not antidepressants,” says Dr. Luke Grzeskowiak, professor at Adelaide University.
